<div id="review_3411307332" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3411307332" />
    <a title="Alex Lee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11509598-alex-lee"><img alt="Alex Lee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1343936414p2/11509598.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3411307332?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex Lee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex Lee" href="/user/show/11509598-alex-lee">Alex Lee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11509598-alex-lee?shelf=psyche">psyche</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11509598-alex-lee?shelf=2020">2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11509598-alex-lee?shelf=impressive">impressive</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11509598-alex-lee?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11509598-alex-lee?shelf=mystical">mystical</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3411307332" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10294259878806781946">I wouldn&apos;t expect what starts off as an book about emotions to be this concise or deep in wrapping up the Western philosophical tradition with its religious tradition. But it is concise and deep despite being fairly short. Tillich is capturing what it means in an emotional/pragmatic way to be in the world -- which in some sense is what philosophy and religion attempts to address, if from very different directions.<br/><br/>In some ways, Tillich still requires a transcendental ground. While he captures the</span>
  <span id="freeText10294259878806781946" style="display:none">I wouldn't expect what starts off as an book about emotions to be this concise or deep in wrapping up the Western philosophical tradition with its religious tradition. But it is concise and deep despite being fairly short. Tillich is capturing what it means in an emotional/pragmatic way to be in the world -- which in some sense is what philosophy and religion attempts to address, if from very different directions.<br /><br />In some ways, Tillich still requires a transcendental ground. While he captures the existentialist "revolt" as thinkers realize that God within Christianity is a God enframed within a system, he still remarks places that system in a limited way by reasserting it in a larger position, as the "God above God". That was a little disappointing. Written in the early 20th century, this makes sense though, as the latest forms of thinking still require a universalist position. Nonetheless, Tillich to some degree anticipates the postmodern turn, whereby transcendence is echoed as an evaluation criteria that is its spectre, a shadow of the rejected "up front" position of universality.<br /><br />This is still a book worth reading, but it is still intellectually constrained within its intellectual milieu.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10294259878806781946" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


